h3. Issue Summary
Trying to upgrade Jira using the {{response.varfile}} as described [here|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver/unattended-installation-938846846.html] fails.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Download a Jira installer;
# Upgrade Jira;
# Use the created {{<installation-directory>/.install4j/response.varfile}} to make a second upgrade.

h3. Expected Results
A successful upgrade.

h3. Actual Results

We are presented with these messages in the terminal:
{noformat}
Unpacking JRE ...
Starting Installer ...
The installation directory has been set to /opt/atlassian2/jirasoftware.
It appears that JIRA is already installed in the directory you selected.  Please choose a different directory.
{noformat}

h3. Workaround

In the {{response.varfile}} file, this line:
{noformat}
sys.confirmedUpdateInstallationString=False
{noformat}
Should actually look like this:
{noformat}
sys.confirmedUpdateInstallationString=true
{noformat}

Just make this replacement, and now the upgrade should happen successfully.

h3. Issue Summary

Following code execution causes validation failure when app user and session user's locale differs:

{code:java}
public UpdateValidationResult validateUpdate(ApplicationUser user, Long issueId, IssueInputParameters issueInputParameters)
.
.
validateAndUpdateIssueFromFields(user, copiedIssue, issueInputParameters, fieldValuesHolder, errorCollection, i18n, getUpdateFieldScreenRenderer(issue), true, null);
.
.
validateAndPopulateParams(user, issue, issueInputParameters, fieldValuesHolder, operationContext, localCollection, i18n, fieldScreenRenderer);
.
.
validateAndPopulateParamsWithoutScreenCheck(user, issue, issueInputParameters, fieldValuesHolder, operationContext, errorCollection, i18n, fieldScreenRenderer);
.
.
orderableField.populateFromIssue(fieldValuesHolder, issue);
{code}


The formatter for date we are using is DateFieldFormatImpl and it by default seems to be doing this:

{code:java}
DateTimeFormatter systemTimeZoneFormatter = dateTimeFormatterFactory.formatter().forLoggedInUser().withSystemZone();
        dateFormatter = systemTimeZoneFormatter.withStyle(DateTimeStyle.DATE);
        datePickerFormatter = systemTimeZoneFormatter.withStyle(DateTimeStyle.DATE_PICKER);
{code}

so for locale sensitive field like dates, this is going to pose problem if the inputs from issue were from App User specific locale.

h3. Steps to Reproduce

- Use default issue service to validateUpdate the issue input parameters created originally by a app user with different locale and issue service invoked by session user with a different locale.
- Run the issue service via a listener tied to any issue updates.

h3. Expected Results

No validation failure regardless of app user and session user's locale differences.

h3. Actual Results

{noformat}
Invalid date format
{noformat}
The validation of input parameters before Issue Update is done by using the language settings of the app user but the re-injected parameters (during this validation) are formatted with the language settings of the session user.
With such context present with incompatible languages settings, the call fails with *invalid date format.*

h3. Workaround

- Developers are forcing validation on only present fields by applying(if not date field is present or is not mandatory) 
{code:java}
updateIssueInputParameters.setRetainExistingValuesWhenParameterNotProvided(true, true);
{code}

Another way around would be to switch the session (JiraAuthenticationContext) to the technical user. Pretty much similar to what we have done here [JRASERVER-42609|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-42609]

The business need is that I can run JQL as these columns are not displayed when running the JQL:
{code:java}
project = pvs and Satisfaction is not EMPTY and "Satisfaction Comment" ~ great and "Satisfaction date" >= 2020-01-01
{code}
and then I can add all 3 columns to the results set view in Jira.
